Namaste madam,

Some traditions in Orissa recommend Dasa Mahavidyas as pala=
na devata. I too taught it as that is what my guru Pt Sanjay Rath taught me=
.
But, later, as I understood Mahavidyas better, I stopped suggesting them =
for material purposes. Vidya is knowledge. Mahavidya is supreme knowledge. =
The only supreme knowledge is that of Self, that which removes all cravings=
 and aversions from the mind and makes one equanimous and detached. Mahavid=
yas represent various facets of that knowledge.
Though Dhoomavati, Ugra Tar=
a, Kala Bhairava etc are worshiped in a smashan normally, that is not neces=
sary. The more important thing is that only those whose *mind* is like a sm=
ashan (with various desires and cravings burnt and nearly reduced to ashes)=
 should worship them. Then they can help one overcome the remaining few bas=
ic desires (that are far tougher to overcome!) and remove any traces of I-n=
ess, so that one is liberated.
It is unwise to pray to Bagalamukhi for vict=
ory in court cases or to Dhoomavati for getting a job or to Chhinnamasta fo=
r getting money, though some astrologers suggest those mantras based on cha=
rt. Better pray to "regular" deities for such purposes. For example, worshi=
p Ganesha for Ketu in your example!
One should approach Mahavidyas only for=
 liberation.
Of course, if you approach them for money, career etc, it is n=
ot that something terrible will happen. Most likely, the deity will not res=
pond, i.e. nothing will happen. In an extremely rare case, the deity may re=
spond and something terrible may happen.
But, if that is the case, it means=
 that the native was actually ready for the lessons taught by that deity an=
d the resulting spiritual progress, though the native did not realize it or=
 want it.
Best regards,
Narasimha
